{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_groot_ver01/data/sn87062224/00514156888/1957101801/0678.xml":{"full_text":"MILFORD CHRONICLE\nESTABLISHED OCTOBER 4, 1878\nTHEO. TOWNSEND\nEditor and Proprietor from 1878 to 1918\nMILFORD CHRONICLE PUBLISHING COMPANY\n10 TO I\u00ab SO\u00dcTH W\u00dcST FRONT STREBT\nMILFORD, DELAWARE\nPUBLISHERS\n_President\n_Vice-President\n.Secretary-Treasurer\nQ. Marshall Townsend\nVlrglnia S. Townsend.\nTheodore Townsend\n_Editor\nManaging Editor\nG- Marchai! Townsend\nRobert H. Yerkes\nExclusive National Advertising Representative\nGreater Weeklies\nItew York Chicago Detroit Philadelphia\nSubscription Terms\nUf Mail\u2014In Delaware, $2 50 s Tsar\nOutside of Delaware. S3.00 a Tear\n.Biz Cents\nBtngle Copies.\nPHONE\u2014MILFORD 4521\nAddrcoa ail communications to the Milford Chronicle\nPublishing Company, Milford, Delaware\nSectoral as second-class matter March 3, 1879 at the\npost office at Milford, Dal., under Act ot March 3, 1S79\nDELAWARE'S LEADING WEEKLY NEWSPAPER\nThe Milford Chronicle Is Delaware's largest weekly\nnewspaper\u2014both in size of paper, number of pages printed,\nvolume of news carried, and lineage of advertising pre\nsented each Issue. All advertising Is sold on a basis ol\na guaranteed circulation of over 7,000 copies each Issue.\nMEMBER OF' THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is entitled exclusively to the\nuse for republication of all the local news printed In\nthis newspaper, as well as all AP news dispatches.\nFRIDAY, OCTOBER 18, 1957\nSAFE HUNTING\nThe season for hunting has begun and,\nunless 1957 is an exception to previous years,\nthe newspapers will report numerous instan\nces involving the wounding or killing of\nhunters by accident.\nNearly every community in the nation\nhas, at one time or another, experienced the\nsense of futile grief which follows a tragedy\nin the fields. The accident, in the absence of\nhuman error, could have been avoided in\nmost instances.\nDespite the knowledge that firearms are\ndangerous, human beings often take a chance\nand, by so doing, take the life of someone\nelse. We have seen several collections of\nsafety rules, designed to warn hunters of\ndanger. The following eleven, which were\nsent out by the Conservation Department of\nthe State of New York some time ago, de\nserves wide circulation and study by all those\nwho plan to take to the fields and woods in\nsearch of game\nm Npvpr carrv loaded cruns in automo\ni l g automo\nbiles or other vehicles.\n2 birdS keep\nP\nn oaain I?* never point a gun in the\ndirection of your companion.\n(4) In climbing over stone walls and\nlances, first break or unload, your gun.\n(5) A bird quartering to the right in the\nvicinity of your companion should never be\nfired on by a hunter on the extreme left, or\nvice versa.\n(6) Never leave a loaded gun standing\nagainst a tree or lying on the ground where\na dog may get at it.\n(7) Always keep your gun pointed away\nfrom your comnanion when you stop to talk,\n(0 r n i*\n(8) In handing a gun to a person for in\nspection, be su it.is\n(9) Never shoot in che direcUon of your\nf\nrrL\u00c4or w r\u00c4i \u201e\u00b0sTi a\u201e*\ngerous chance.\n(10) Carry a gun pointed down to the\nleft. If you shoot left-handed, walk at the\nextreme right of your companion.\n11 At all times, be careful.\nTHREE BILLIONS FOR LIQUOR\nAmericans spent three times as much on\naicoholic beverages in 1956 as they contri\nbuted to all churches, religious bodies and\nwelfare organizations. This shocking fact is\nreported by the Methodist Boa^d of Temper\nance.\nThe report cited figures of the Depart\nment of Commerce which showed that $10,\n500,000,000 was spent for liquor by Ameri\ncans last year, while the amount given for\nreligious and welfare purposes was $3,746,\n000,000. If these statistics are correct, then\nlast year's liquor expenditure was $410,000,\n000 higher than that for the year before.\nThe same statistical reported stated that\nAmericans spent $2,416,000,000 for books,\nmagazines and newspapers last year, $3,296,\n000,000 for physicians and $1,173,000,000\nfor medical care and hospitalization insur\nIt is also interesting, we think, to point\nout that our people spent almost twice as\nmuch for tobacco last year than they gave to\nreligious and welfare activities. According\nto the report, a total of $5,681,000,000 went\nup in the smoke from cigarettes, cigars and\nP'P\u00ae?*,.\nBelieving that the above figures speak\nfor themselves, we will make no further\ncomment.\nar.ee\nREADY FOR WINTER\nThe first snap of cold in the air usually\nalerts even procrastinating home owners to\nget ready for winter. Storm doors are put up,\nscreens are stored, the snow shovel is placed\nwhere it will be handy.\nFor the motorist, too, preparations for\nwinter are wise. It's a good idea to have the\ncar checked. Breakdowns on a cold morning\ncan be mighty inconvenient.\nIt is especially sensible to check all the\nsafety features of your car before winter.\nTires that are too worn w'on't stop your car\nin time on a wet, icy road. Brakes that\nwere good enough to get by in fair w'eather\nmight not be adequate when roads are slip\npery. Windshield wipers that work properly\nmight mean the difference between avoiding\nan accident and being a victim.\nThe good driver adjusts his mental atti\ntude with the seasons, too. He know's that\ndriving when the weather is bad create spe\ncial hazards, and he drives more carefully.\nAccidents can happen to anyone, but they are\nless likely to happen to you if you give the\nsame thought to safety that you give to the\nimportant details of running your home or\ndoing your job. The careful driver is the\nsafe driver.\nPREPARE FOR ASIAN FLU\nAll too often epidemics have struck with\nout warning in the United States, finding us\nunprepared. The same cannot be said of\nAsian flu. We know that this highly infec\ntious disease is imminent and is expected to\nbecome critical this winter. The Red Cross\ntells us there are certain things we can do\nto be ready for it.\nAsian flu is a much less lethal type of res\npiratory ailment than the Spanish influenza\nwhich swept the country in the closing\nmonths of World War I and claimed an es\ntimated 635,000 lives. But the time to pre\npare for it is growing short.\nRed Cross has already set in motion its\ncontributions to an effective nation-wide com\nmunity preparedness plan. The national or\nganization has asked those Red Cross chap\nters that include the 14-hour Care of the Sick\nand Injured course in their chapter program\nto increase the number of classes available,\nto incorporate special information concern\ning the care of Asian flu victims in the home,\nand to recommend to community residents\nthat at least one member of each household\ntake the training course. All Red Cross chap\nters have been supplied with fact sheets con\ntaining pertinent information about the\nAsian flu. Women already trained as volun\nteer Red Cross nurse's aides are being alert\ned, and other women urged to enroll in the\n40-hour nurse's aide training course quali\nfying them to assist professonal nurses in\nhospitals and clinics during outbreaks of the\ndisease. There will be need also for many\nother trained Red Cross volunteers to trans\nport patients to and from hospitals and clin\nics, to assist in preparing and serving meals,\n\nThe head of one of the major farm equip\nment companies, speaking at a meeting of\nFarm Equipment Institute in Chicago,\ndiscussed this idea in torthnght terms. It is\nof great importance to the equipment mak\ners in that they are or g anize d by the UAW\n_ and so it algo f t importance to\ntheir customers.\netc.\nOnset of Asian flu is rapid, with fever\nup to 103 or 104 degrees. But there is no\nreason for panic. The need is for prepared\nness.\nDon't wait until the fever strikes.\nA NEW KIND OF INFLATION\nSome of the labor unions\u2014led by the Uni\nted Auto Workers\u2014have as their next major\ngoal a shorter work week without any re\nduction in pay.\nThe spokesman said that the shorter\nwork-week idea \"ignores the economic facts\n0 f \u00fcf e> an( j that it amounts to demanding\nmuch more money for much less productive\ntime. That, obviously, can lead only to re\nnewed and stimulated price inflation.\nHe then turned to escalator clauses, which\ntie wage adjustments to the government's\nBureau of Labor Statistics cost-of-living in\ndex, and which are a feature of union con\ntracts in a wide range of industries. These\nclauses, he said, bring about a \"new kind of\ninflation\". He added \"It starts with infla\nti<m, which turns into cost inflation and ends\ni? P r j ce inflation. The resulting price infla\ntion in turn raises the B. L. S. cost-of-hvmg\nindex and automat i ca ll y _through operation\nof contract escalator clauses\u2014triggers an\nother round of increases which con\nthe cyde a d bwomes seif\np\nR is certainly time the unions practiced a\nreasonable amount of restraint in their poli\ncl /f an <J demands. If inflation should get out\nf hand\u2014a danger which certainly exists to\nday\u2014no group will be hit harder than labor.\nSPUTNIK IMPLICATIONS\nThe military and political implications of\nthe Russians' scientific accomplishment in\nlaunching the satellite they call Sputnik are\ngrave for the United States and the free\nworld. The Russians appear clearly to be\nahead of the United States in the race for an\nintercontinental ballistic missile. Also, the\nR\u00fcssians have already begun to squeeze the\nfuflest propaganda advantage from the great\nachievement of their scientists.\nand our own allies will become apprehensive\nthat American propaganda has misfired,\nThey are deriding the United States, and\nboasting. Asian and African nations will be\nimpressed by what the Russians have done,\nThe entire American propaganda and in\nformational policy needs immediately to be\nassessed and revised. Madison Avenue tech\nniques are no weapons with which to explain\na nd counter the Sputnik, And our scientists\nmust be given all that is needed to permit\nthem to succeed in catching up with and\nsurpassing the Russians,\nWith will, imagination, intelligence and\nserious determination we can erase or neu\ntralize the advantages which the Russians\nhave gained. And it must be emphasized that\nmilitary and political implications of the\nRussian achievement are what concern us,\nnot the contribution their scientists have\nmade to knowledge.\nVT _\nproposals. Now an appropriation bill for\nhundreds of millions of dollars is often pass\ne( a the end of a session by a voice vote,\nwith few if any congressmen having more\nthan the vaguest idea of what it contains,\nCongress would gain in popular respect\nif it systematized its proceedings on some\nline like that suggested by Senator Magnu\nson.\nHOW TO SAVE MONEY\nOne reason for Congressional extrava\ngance is that our lawmakers give only half\nattention to money bills, sandwiching them\nin between other legislation which often is\nmuch dearer to Congressional hearts. This\nsituation would be remedied if a bill by Sen\nator Warren G. Magnuson of Washington\nbecame law*.\n\nSenator Magnuson would have Congress\nmeet annually, from second Monday in No\nvember to December 31, for the sole purpose\nof dealing with revenue and appropriation\nbills. All other legislation would be postpon\ned to a session beginning in January.\nThis would do away with the haste and\nconfusion which too often attends financial\nOUR THREE-STAGER THAT WENT PHF F F T\n\"v \u2014-C r 7\n'0^\n-r\niS\n\"wsm*\n\nV.\u00bb\n-'J\n'V\nm\nBfi\n\n\n\nt?-.\n-V\nSfi\n\nmm\nW&f\u00df.\n1\n\n\\L\ni\nS\n\nV\nI ill\nn\nV\n:\u00e7\nI\nj\n\n\n\nc\no j\u00a3i> rr\u00a3\nCflfcS\n\n\n\u00a3r.\n\u00fc\n\u25a0ik\n'v\n\nas\nW.\nY\nMS\n.A\nm\n\nw\n'U\nTn\nA\nvrjj\nA\n\nn\nm\n\n\n\n7\n\nC\nWashington Letter By Robert Nelson Taylor\nRealistic \"Foreign Aid\n\nEncouraging more private U. S.\ninvestment abroad is the U. S.\nforeign policy objective that makes\nthe most sense from any realistic\nviewpoint. It helps friendly na\ntions to develop their own re\nsources. It counters communist ec\nonomic pressures. It helps reduce\nforeign aid costs and thus helps cut\nour tax burdens. And, most im\nportant. it gives the U. S. investor\na personal stake in the broad\ngrowth our investments stimulate\nthroughout the Free World.\nSince 1954, the relatively new but\ngrowing Canadian investment com\npares have effectively demostrated\nhow to implement this policy.\nThese are Canadian mutual fund\ninvestment companies publicly own\ned by U. S. shareholders. Encour\naged and organized under existing\nU. S. and Canadian laws, they in\nvest principally in Canadian secur\nities, and they are prepared to in\nvest further in other Free World\nnations offering incentives and\ngrowth opportunities comparable to\nthose of Canada.\nIn little more than three years,\naccording to the Committee of\nCanadian Investment Companies,\nmore than 105,000 U. S. citizens\nhave put more than $380,00o,000 to\nwork in Canadian and other Free\nWorld securities\u2014an average stake\nof about $3,000 per U. S. investor.\nCanada, which significantly has\nnever sought U. S. \"foreign aid\"\nfunds, has welcomed this type of\nU. S. investment because it sup\nplies essential capital without in\ntruding in Canadian affairs. These\ncompanies, by policy, are minority\nshareholders maintaining broadly\ndiversified investments in many\nCanadian companies\u2014but not exer\ncising or seeking control. They are\niterested in foreign securities' in\nvestment values and benefits for\ntheir shareholders\u2014not in domi\nnation.\nMoreover, these companies keep\ntheir resources continuously at\nwork in the economy of Canada and\nother nations because Canadian\nand U. S. laws permit them to re\ninvest their investment income at\nlow tax cost to their shareholders.\nThis principle of pooling capital\nof thousands of U. S. managed\nportfolio investments abroad has ef\nfectively contributed to our foreign\neconomic policy\u2014with benefit to\nU. S. investors.\nIt is highly desireable that this\ntested type of private foreign in\nBabson Discusses Winter Business Outlook And\nRussian Satellite\nBabson Park, Mass., October 17.\nDuring most of this year business\nhas shown basic stability, despite\nthe readjustments which many in\ndustries have encountered and with\nwhich some are still having to\ncontend. The total Physical Volume\nof Business is currently only a trifle\nbelow the high range of recent\nmonths, and it just a few per\ncentage points lower than the first\nquarter peak for the year to date.\nDuring the summer, many busi\nnesses have been drawn downward\nbecause of seasonal influences such\nas hot weather and vacation ab\nsences. Therefore, I expect busi\nness during coming months to be\nmoderately upward, helped by the\nRussian Satellite.\nHowever, the improvement de\npends also upon,basic consumer at\ntitudes, which can change from day\nto day. Recent surveys on con\nsumer behavior and attitudes in\ndicate that buyers are becoming\nmore price-conscious and more se\nlective. Nevertheless, manufacturers\nare hopeful that their plans and\noutput schedules for coming months\nwill tally closely with the purchas\ning plans of consumers, which are\nstill continuing upward.\nThe Auto Outlook\nThe automobile industry is a\noellwether of forthcoming trends.\nDealers' stocks are currently near\n600.000. most of them 1957 cars, with\nonly a sprinkling of 1958 models.\nThus far, there has been little ap\nj P^ensio\" regarding the jze^of\npeful that October sales will\nat least approach those of a year\nvestment be encouraged. For it is\nclear that, given proper climates\nand reasonable incentives here and\nabroad, it can succeed where un\nrealistic \"aid\" projects have failed,\n\nTime To Face The Muzhiks\nThe first American artificial\nmoon with broadcasting facilities\n\u2014built and launched in full color\nin our popular magazines long,\nlong ago\u2014will be lofted into the\nnothingness next March, while a\nbeepless dummy will be sent up in\na test shot in December.\nThis is President Eisenhower's\nforecast, made to his press confer\nence as Russia's sputnik continued\nits 30-minute round-the-world\nflights for the fifth day and chall\nenged the World's Series for news\npaper space. The nose cone and\nshell of the third-stage of the roc\nket that sent it orbiting 560 miles\nup were following sputnik around\n\u2014as if to underscore the Russian\ntriumph.\nThe President paid his respects\nto \"the very powerful thrust in\ntheir (the Russian) rocketry\", but\nsaid of the satellite itself, \"that\ndoes not raise my apprehensions,\nnot one iota\". Nevertheless, Ameri\nca's top experts on satellites, roc\nkets and missiles trooped into the\nWhite House the next day to attend,\nwith Mr. Eisenhower, the regular\nmeeting of the National Security\nCouncil: and Neil H. McElroy, our\nnew Defense Secretary, told news\nmen he was studying ways and\nmeans of speeding up the missile\nprogram. Following this came an\nother high-level White House meet\ning on the ICBM \u2014which Russia\nhas, and we haven't.\nSputnik, even though it may have\nslowed, dropped into the earth's\natmosphere and burned up before\nyou read this, has been of immense\nvalue to Russia, providing the Reds\nwith a psychological victory over\nwhich the world is still gasping.\nYet sputnik may have performed\nan even greater service for the\nU. S. If it has punctured official\ncomplacency, reduced some swelled\nheads and frightened some of the\njealousy out of our ranking de\nfenders, it has served us well. It\nmay even have shaken our Cen\ntral Intelligence Agency whidh ap\npears, again, to have been taken\nunaware.\nWe have been gravely assured\nby various officials, from the Presi\ndent down, that there was no in\nternational \"race\" to mount the\nago.\nThe slight degree of optimism\namong automobile makers is help\ning to buoy the steel industry,\nwhich continues to hope for a\nstrengthening of orders. Though\nsuch orders have been coming in\ngradually, nearby weeks may see a\ngreater rush as the remainder of the\nplants change over to the produc\ntion of 1958 cars. Appliance ma ers\nare also proceeding cautiously with\nrespect to orders since sales have\nbeen disappointing so far this year.\nHowever, as inventories in these\nlines register declines factory out\nput Should ia y mif.harder\nContraction Industry\nAnother major steel user, the\ncontraction industry, appears to\nhave been taking a breather, al\nthough *he latest month's figures\nshow a more-than-seasonal rise\nafter the disappointing earlier\nweeks. Work stoppages in\ncement industry caused short\nages of concrete products in some\nsectors. There are, however, more\nbasic reasons for the slower pace\nin building, such as scarcity of\nmoney and the partial fulfillment\nof demand for housing. Sustaining\nstrength, however, should be evi\ndent in public works utilities, and\nroad bu\u00fcding\nBeyond the conundrum of what\nthe consumer is going to do with\nSK income? s f 'conLmer-\u00abp.\u201e-1\nfected *by n low\u00ab- Expenditures by\n^bSSTSe^\u00c4*\nthe\nfirst earth satellite. But we find it\nvery hard to believe\u2014in view of\nthe tremendous publicity build-up\n\u2014that those in charge of our pro\ngram were not trying to do just\nthat. The fact that the original\nsatellite appropriation of $22 mil\nlion was boosted to $66 million and\nthen to $110 million would also\nseem to suggest a certain amount\nof pressure on the project.\nBut, whether therte was a \"race\"\nor not, it cannot be denied that we\nlost.\n\n\"He Loves Me, He Loves Me Not''\nWe would have said last July\nthat this nation would soon be\nbooned with a visit from our Presi\ndent's wartime friend and sub\nsequent pen-pal, Marshal Georgi\nZhukov. In fact, Georgi would prob\nably have said so, too. This was just\nafter the President had been ask\ned if such a visit might be useful.\nIt seems, according to the recent\nand extensive interview of The\nNew York Times' James Reston\nwith Nikita Khrushchev, that the\nRussian translation of the Presi\ndent's answer was\u2014rin a word\u2014\n\"Da!\". The Russians therefore told\nMr. Dulles that if an invitation\nwere issued. Marshal Zhukov would\naccept it. But Mr. Dulles said\n\"Nyet\". The President's remarks,\nhe said, were \"a' hypothetical an\nswer to a hypothetical question\".\nAnd Mr. Khrushchev is still burn\ning.\nAsked about this report at his\npress conference. President Eisen\nhower declared that no rebuff was\nintended but that the Secretary of\nState had pointed out that bi\nlateral talks would be a bad thing\nat the time\u2014when the disarmament\ntalks were going on in London.\nThus it would appear that the\n\"Butcher of Bucharest\", as he has\nbeen called, will not be ringing the\nWhite House doorbell. Yet Jay G.\nHayden, writing in The Washing\nton Star, concludes a lengthy ar\nticle of the incident in these\nwords: \"Even so, Marshal Zhukov\nmay arrive in Washington before\nlong.\"\nOur mental picture of the Mar\nshall who has been elevated to the\nPresidium of the Supreme Soviet\nsince his successful mission to\nHungary, and who is widely re\ngarded as \"the strong man\" of\nRussia, shows him pulling the\npetals off a daisey and saying (in\nRussian, of course) \"He loves me,\nhe loves me not.\"\ntracts, such as aircraft workers\nan( j others employed in these towns\ndependent upon military payrolls,\nRusian Satellite may, however,\nc hange all this\nWhat About Employment!\n\u00abp^ose who are laid off will- be\nj egg eap er to S p ent j an d will hesi\ntate gQ further in debt while\nthose wbo re maiu on the payi oil\nm become more cautious about\ndi 0n the other hand, due\nJ he j iod of the\nconsumer has become ac\ncustomed tQ an increas ingly higher\nstandard of living And it is far\nto adjust one's tastes down\nthan raige them ard>\nAll in all, coming months should\nshow a modest improvement over\nthe lows of the summer months.\nBut the degree of improvement is\ndependent on a revival of consumer\nexpenditures, which in turn are af\nfected by capital outlays and by\nchanges in Government spending,\nwhich could be increased as a re\n,\u00abU of the Roman Satellite ana\nta^tora'h^lje'n mej\u00efy'hlL'l\u00f9tlnl\n\u00e4\u00e4\u00e4\nHigher wages are partly respon\nsible for the continued rise in per\nsonal incomes. However, these in\ncreases in pay rates are a cause for\nconcern to producers, since they\nadd to the cost of doing business.\nCoupled with lower sales in certain\nlines, they further squeeze profits.\nConclusions\nIN THE AIR FORCE\nh\n\nBy Eiain\u00ab Towntand Oickarson\n3531 Mayo\nTopeka, Kansas\nOctober 14, 1957\nDear Friends\nHayes and his crew are naturally\npleased to represent their wing at\nthe SAC wide competition in Flor\nida this month, but it certainly has\nbeen rough on their nervous system\nthus far and the competition\ndoesn't commence until the 30th of\nthis month. Last week Hayes and\nDon Miller (air craft commander\u2014\na captain) and Dave Baugh (the co\npilot\u2014a first lieutenant) spent three\nbusy days at MacDill AFB in Flor\nida. This was their time to practice\nrun on the targets of the competi\ntion. Hayes said they flew, mis\nsion planned, grabbed quick meals,\ndebriefed (go over their missions\nafter they have flown) and slept six\nhour each night. As a result of this\ngruelling schedule Hayes came\nhome Friday night minus four\npounds. He seemed so tense from\nall the strain of striving for per\nfection that sleeping pills were re\nquired!\nNot only does your crew depend\non you, but so does your squadron,\nyour squadron comnsanding officer,\nthe wing that you represent, the\ndivision, the Air Force you repre\nsent (Eighth-Westover, Massachus\netts) and of course SAC. All these\npeople seem to be breathing down\nyour neck as the results of the\ncompetition start rolling in. I'll\nbe mighty happy when the whole\nbusiness is over. Hayes, as naviga\ntor on the crew, is responsible for\nthe bombing results and navigation,\nwhich the competition is based on.\nIt's a heavy load to carry on his six\nfoot frame and its weight will\ndoubtlessly make my husband shed\na few more pounds before it is\nall over.\nWhile Hayes was away this week\nI attended a party for Irene Hall,\neven though she didn't. Irene is\nher parents' only child. Each sum\nmer as soon as school is out she\ngoes home to New England to spend\nthe summer with her parents, so\nthey may enjoy the three months\nwith their only grandchildren.\nWhile Irene was still in New Eng\nland her Lieutenant Colonel hut\nband received concurrent orders\nfor all of them to go PCS (perma\nnane change of station) to England\nfor three years. It is the custom of\nour bridge club to give each de\nparting member (and the bridge\nclub changes monthly almost) an\n13,855\nSussex County\nReal Estate Transfers\nBranch A. Passwaters and Dora\nL., to Alton P. Passwaters and Syl\nvia J., Seaford Hundred,\nsquare feet.\nMiles B. Hitchens Heirs, to Er\nnest A. Timmons and Florence S. r\nDelmar, 0.279 acre.\nLorenzo B. Whaley and Manie H.,\nto Robert Middleyon and Eliza\nbeth, Broad Creek Hundred, 247 x\n260 x 136 x 282.\nSouth Bethany Corporation to\nReese F. Cropper, Baltimore Hd.,\nlot 69, Blk. 4, Sec. B.\nRuth Edna Brittingham and Leon\nO., to Jacob H. West, Jr., and Betty\nI., Dagsboro Hd., 25,700 sq. ft.\nLeon O. Brittingham and Ruth\nEdnji, to Frank S. Parker and Mil\ndred, Dagsboro Hd., 26,400 sq. ft.\nHenry H. Allman and Tacq S..\nWilliam H. Thompson and Marga\nret 3., to Irvin B. Powell and Ida\nT., Baltimore Md., lot 9, Blk. 110,\nlots 11 and E. 55' of lot 12, Blk.\n110\nLoleta O. Walls to Raymond H.\nFleetwood and Almeta C., George\ntown Md., lot 4.\nSouth Bethany Corp. to Reese F.\nCropper, Baltimore Hd., lot 68, Blk.\n4, Sec. B.\nWililam M. Perrott and Nettie V.\nto Albert R. Johnson, Lewe? and\nRehoboth Hd., 45,000 sq. ft.\nGeorge J. Schulz and Mary D\u201e to\nRichard K. Thompson, Sr., and\nMary Y., Baltimore Hd., lot 515 and\n5. Mi of lot 516.\nWilliam V. Davidson to WUliam\nHitch and Lillian W\u201e Cedar Creek\nHd., lots 3 and 4, and part of lot 2.\nRoland F. Scott and Sara P., to\nthe Town of Se.'byville, Baltimore\nHd.. 25,000 sq. ft.\nSussex Realty Co. to Reese W.\nSmith and Eva Helen Smith,\nGeorgetown Hd., lot.\nSussex Shore Realty Co. to Rob\nert J. Toomey and John J., Balti\nmore Hd., lot 4, Blk. 3.\nJenny P. Jefferson and Estella P.\nGyles to Johnnie L. Pearson, Jr.,\nand Cornelia B., Georgetown Hd..\nNorth Shores, Inc., to Edward A. j\nBeard and Phyllis H., Lewes and\n0.606 acre.\nLeroy L. Rust and Phyllis A., to\nJames P. Johnson, Cedar Creek Hd.,\nlot 8 and S. of lot 7.\nHerbert Barnes and Jessie B. to\nEthel Hatton, Lewes and Rehoboth\nHd., lot 10, Blk. 38.\nNorth Shores, Inc., to Peter T.\nBeardsley and Elsie M\u201e Lewes and\nRehoboth Hd., lot 17.\nHolland H. Cooper Heirs to Ger\ntrude Byrd Cooper, Little Creek\nHd.. 2 lots.\nAlvah W. Lloyd and Harriette A.,\nto W'illiam Downing and Anna E.,\nNanticoke Hd., 11 acres.\nHarry E. Dukes and Bertha A., to\nEdith M. Hudson and Suzanne Dor\nis, Dagsboro Hd., lot 1.\nWilliam James Hopkins, Jr., and\nMary Anne J., to Charles S. Cooper\nand Jeanne L., Town of Laurel, lot.\nCharles S. Cooper and Jeannie L.,\nto Edward H. Ralph and Laurann\nR\u201e Little Creek Hd.. 17 acres.\nCharles S. Cooper and Jeanne, to\nDouglas G. Cooper and Winnie E\u201e\nSeaford Hd., lots 8, 9, 10, 11. 15 and\n15 Sec. D.\n177\nRehohotn no io-i\n,\u00ae|V? sex lU C10\nPhillips and Ida S.. Georgetow\nHd.. lots 01 a-s, 00 oa. 1\nGracie M. Dennis and Joseph, to\nClinton Luff and Bertha Pauline,\nGreenwood, 5,000 sq. ft\nGiles Willie Lee and Marie Annie\nto Inrtnjj W Trice, Inc.. Sca.orn\n1 Paris Thomas and Lydia A., to\ns r\nearring or handkerchief shower.\nThe shower we had, minus the\nguest of honor. Two of the girls in\nthe bridge club were the hostesses\nand I was asked to be one of two\nto pour punch. The champagne\npunch and vodka punch had been\ntinted fuchsia, the flowers were a\ngorgeous purple and the purple\ncandles in the silver candelabras\nmade a most attractive picture.\nFuchsia and purple are Irene's\ncolors and every one could appre\nciate her choice looking at the love\nly table.\nI was asked to begin serving the\npunch at my end of the table and\nsurreptitiously behind me stood one\nof the hostesses trying to get her\nguests off guard in a flash picture\nthat she would send to Irene. Why\nI didn't fall in the punch bowl I'll\nnever know, but the flash bulb was\nan inferior one and exploded with\na thundering noise. At the time I\nwas serving the base commander's\nwife and the noise frightened her\nso she threw her fuchsia beverage\nall over that gorgeous table'. Glass\nfrom the bulb shattered all over\neveryone and we're not too sure\neven now that it didn't sift down\ninto the bottom of the silver punch\nbowl. It started the party off with\na definite bang that's for certain!\nWith my gift to Irene 1 wrote\none of my silly rhymes. Want to\nhear it?\nWhat a shock it was to hear\nThat you wouldn't be back.\nGives us faith that there are for\nothers\nGood assignments in SAC.\nIf, when you're settled in England\nAnd they keep Colonel Hall on the\nrun\nHave him call for \u00e0 good navigator\nNamed Lewis Hayes Dickerson.\nWith all that silver, china and cash\nmere\nYour tour will be happy and serene.\nI certainly am most envious.\nAnd now call you \"Lucky Irene.\"\nHave I told you that the people\nwho bought our Likens-Foster\nhome here on Mayo are being\ntransferred to another job with the\nAir Force Dei ot? This necessi\ntates their selling this house again,\nafter never having lived in it. It\nmeans we're open for inspection\nagain and the tour is just about\nready to commence!\nI'll write to you next week.\nAlways,\nElaine Townsend Dickerson\nA., Lewes and Rehoh'oth Hd., 291.0\nx 145.0 x 206.37 x 160.0.\nJames Evans and Lois, to David\nJ. L\u00f6ng and Betty Jean, Baltimore\nHd., acre.\nRehoboth by the Sea Realty Co.,\nto I. D. Short Co., Rehoboth, lots 5,\n7, and 8, Blk. 25.\nJohn L, Briggs and Co., to Wil\nliam F. Byram and Ruth F., George\ntown Hd., lot H.\nSwannendael, Inc., to Otha H.\nFurniss and Betty M., Lewes and\nRehoboth Hd., lot 41.\nWilliam H. Suthard Heirs to Har\nry E. Heath and Gladys E. and\nRuth, Lewes and Rehoboth Hun\ndred, lot.\nTRINITY\nMiss Maggie Carey of Seattle,\nWashington, has returned home\nafter a three weeks visit with her\nbrother and sister-in-law, Mr. and\nMrs. Lee Carey.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Dill and\ndaughters spent Sunday with their\naunt, Mrs. John Warner at Denton.\nMrs. Warner accompanied them\nhome for a few days.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Walston and\nmother, Mrs. Harry Walston visited\nMr. and Mrs. Dawson Hubaertt of\nConcord, Md., on Sunday after\nnoon.\nMrs. Virginia Hoke ot Bridge\nville, spent Sunday afternoon with\nMiss Charlotte White.\nMr. and Hrs. Samuel Warrington\nand family toenv Sunday with Mrs.\nWarrington's parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nDean Seeley, near Woodenhawk.\nMiss Joyce Warrington was an\novernight guest of Miss Bonnie\nMilspaw on Monday.\nMr. and Mrs. Enos Nichols and\nMrs. W. F. Hastings visited Mr. and\nMrs. Everett Hubbertt and family\nof near Federalsburg on Sunday.\nMrs. Lee Carey and Miss Maggie\nCarey spent Friday evening with\nMrs. Samuel Warrington.\nMrs. Philip Morris of Bridge\nville spent Sunday afternoon with\nher mother, Mrs. James Dill.\nWe are very sorry to report that\nHugh Martin has been confined to\nhis home for the past week because\nof illness.\nRussell Teschner of Newtown,\nPa., was a week-end guest at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. Lee Carey.\nMiss Pamela Coleman had the\nmisfortune to step on a nail, and is\nnow under the care of the doctor.\nMr. and Mrs. Lee Carey and their\nhouse guests, Miss Maggie Carey\nof Seattle, Wash., Russell Teschner\nof Newtown, Pa., and their daugh\nter, Mrs. George Hardesty of\nBridgeville were all Saturday even\ning guests of Mr. and Mrs. Kenneth\nWest.\nThe WSCS of Trinity will meet\non Friday evening, October 18, at\nthe Dublin Hill Community Hall.\nMr. and Mrs. Orville Banning will\nbe the host and hostess.\nHome coming services will be\nheld at Trinity Methodist Church\non Sunday, October 20. Morning\nservices will be in charge c\u00a3 the\npastor. Rev. Gerald Henderson at\n11 o'clock. Afternoon service will\nbe at 2:30 with Rev. Robert E.\nGreen of Milford to deliver the\nmessage. Luncheon will be served\nat the Dublin Hill Community Hall\nbetween the services.\n4 _ TTrttT Dr IT\nALBLQLLRQLE, N. M. A\ndrink known locally as a Flaming\nPurple Passion certainb Ined up\nto its name recently^ The bartender\nwa, mixing dr,nk and alar,edw\nsot.e out once. The^concoction burst\njs?Js:bSi-\".s!L s .'\u00c4\n-4h\nFIRE DRINKERS","height":"25116","width":"20085"}}
